			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Jim Sterling talks about player apathy and the companies that depend on it
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1842097">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							I think this one might be a losing battle. The core might hate it, but the mainstream don't seem to care, and entire generations are now being brought up thinking it's normal through the mobile space. There's always going to be whales who will spend money without actually stopping to think about what they are buying.<br />
<br />
A few weeks ago I was reading a guy complaining that there wasn't anything for him to spend his Konami Metal Gear base coins on. He bought the most expensive pack right when the game came out without even bothering to figure out how many he actually &quot;needed&quot;. Turns out he was able to buy all the extra base slots you could and have most of them left over. Dumb. <br />
<br />
Although since he brings it up, I wonder if Season Passes went away because of negative backlash, or if they simply weren't effective to their purpose. People can complain about all this stuff all they want, but the publishers wouldn't do it if it didn't work. And it works because people buy into it. <br />
<br />
Hype culture in particular kind of bugs me lately. Looking forward to a new game can be fun, but people make stupid decisions in this lust to always have the newest thing the second it comes out. I'm torn though, because publishers probably depend on these first day/week/month sales to be profitable enough to be worth financing the project in the first place.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
