				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Jim Sterling talks about player apathy and the companies that depend on it
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1842276">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							God, he's so annoying. I don't think I'll ever not be annoyed by the over-dramatic behavior seemingly required to become a popular Youtuber. At least he is good at being a jackass, I've seen people try to duplicate the same thing and have it be too obvious that it's 100% forced and fake.<br />
<br />
That Season Pass strategy is the same thing they do with Battlefield. The maps continue to get developed after the main game gets released. It allows people to remain employed working on new content even after a game ships, and prolongs the life of the game. Whether or not that actually has value to you depends on how heavily invested you are in a game's multiplayer, but it is disingenuous to suggest they should be part of the base game. <br />
<br />
No one is twisting your arm making you pay $120 for a video game. Get it for $48 from Best Buy and ignore the Season Pass, or be patient and wait until it gets discounted. I got BF3, BF4, Titanfall, and Garden Warfare all for $5-$10 each. By the time the DLC starts coming out they lower the price of the base game by a ton hoping you would want to stay current, and if you do you get it all bundled for a normal price.<br />
<br />
Hell, the fact that it makes sense for a normal person to wait actually plays to his benefit. If most people wait until it's cheaper, then that is a larger audience to watch HIM play it on streams. I mean, shit, does cynicism in this business really only go one way?
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
